le planet ... [Sami\'s] passion for weird and wonderful wildlife is simply infectious. BETTER READING \'Cleverly presented and strikingly illustrated . . . This fabulous book has a place in all libraries and would also be a wonderful gift for children of all ages\' READPLUS','0734421362','9780734421364',0,'Animals',0.00,0,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=igz4zgEACAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api&fife=w800&format=webp','en','NOT_MATURE','BOOK'),(949,'Mark Twain','Wayne Ashmore','Great Storytellers','2020-08','Mark Twain lived during the time of slavery and the Civil War in the United States. Writing was a way for Mark to express his views on these topics.','179112867X','9781791128678',0,'Juvenile Nonfiction',0.00,32,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=zsJ_zQEACAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api&fife=w800&format=webp','en','NOT_MATURE','BOOK'),(950,'New Hands, New Life','Alex Mihailidis, Jan Andrysek','Không có nhà xuất bản','2017','Everyone uses machines in our daily life -- cars, buses and bikes; computers and phones; washing machines and dryers. Another type of machine is an \"assistive technology\". These enable a man missing a leg to walk, a woman missing an arm to hold objects, and a child in a wheelchair to play a sport. New Hands, New Life offers young readers the opportunity to learn how our bodies work during physical activity and what happens when they don\'t work properly. It shows how exciting advances in technology and science have allowed us to create assistive technologies -- from artificial limbs and wheelchairs to exoskeletons and robots -- that make it possible for someone with a disability to make new abilities. Assistive technologies are especially life-changing for a child who can overcome the challenges of a missing limb or reduced motor function to enjoy a life of learning and play that would be otherwise out of reach. Topics include: The emergence of robotics Anatomy and physiology related to 